    <section id="id1164856949870">
      <title>Homoleptic amides </title>

      <para id="id1164853398903">A homoleptic compound is <emphasis effect="italics">a compound with all the ligands being identical</emphasis>, e.g., M(NH<sub>2</sub>)<sub>n</sub>. A general route to homoleptic amide compounds is accomplished by the reaction of a salt of the desired metal that is soluble in liquid ammonia (<link target-id="id2954606"/>) with a soluble Group 1 amide. The solubility of the Group 1 amides is given in <link target-id="id7826865"/>. Since all amides are insoluble (except those of the Group 1 metals) are insoluble in liquid ammonia, the resulting amide may be readily isolated, e.g., <link target-id="eip-44461"/> and <link target-id="eip-44462"/>. </para>

