    <section id="id7819969">
      <title>Redox reactions</title>
      <para id="id1164853603446">Ammonia is poor as an oxidant since it is relatively easily oxidized, e.g., <link target-id="eip-44463"/> and <link target-id="eip-44464"/>. Thus, if it is necessary to perform an oxidation reaction ammonia is not a suitable solvent; however, it is a good solvent for reduction reactions. </para>


<equation id="eip-44463">   <media id="id1164852986948_media" alt="">
            <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/graphics12-c892.jpg" id="id1164852986948__onlineimage" width="500" print-width="4.5in"/>
          </media></equation>

       


<equation id="eip-44464">   <media id="id1164858129218_media" alt="">
            <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/graphics13-21e5.jpg" id="id1164858129218__onlineimage" width="500" print-width="4.5in"/>
          </media></equation>

       


      <para id="id1164858049531">Liquid ammonia will dissolve Group 1 (alkali) metals and other electropositive metals such as calcium, strontium, barium, magnesium, aluminum, europium, and ytterbium. At low concentrations (ca. 0.06 mol/L), deep blue solutions are formed: these contain metal cations and solvated electrons, <link target-id="eip-44466"/>. The solvated electrons are stable in liquid ammonia and form a complex: [e<sup>-</sup>(NH<sub>3</sub>)<sub>6</sub>].</para>

<equation id="eip-44466">        <media id="id8014751_media" alt="">
          <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/graphics14-1b0e.jpg" id="id8014751__onlineimage" width="500" print-width="4.5in"/>
        </media>
</equation>


      <para id="id1164853676729">The solvated electrons provide a suitable and powerful reducing agent for a range of reactions that are not ordinarily accomplished, e.g., <link target-id="eip-44467"/> and <link target-id="eip-44468"/>. </para>

